# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1921-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] 1905 was the fifth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in third place with a record of 79–74 (.516), 151⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers posted a run differential of -97, the lowest ever by a team with a winning record, breaking the previous record of -81 held by the 1882 Detroit Wolverines; the Tigers lost 48 games by 3 or more runs.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 602 to 512, the largest negative run differential ever for a Major League team with a winning record.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 193,384, eighth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The **1921 Detroit Tigers** finished in sixth place in the American League, 27 games behind the Yankees, with a record of 71–82.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Despite their sixth-place finish, the 1921 Tigers amassed 1,724 hits and a team batting average of .316—the highest team hit total and batting average in American League history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit outfielders Harry Heilmann and Ty Cobb finished No.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] 2 in the American League batting race with batting averages of .394 and .389, and all three Detroit outfielders (Heilmann, Cobb, and Bobby Veach) ranked among the league leaders in batting average and RBIs.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] As early proof of the baseball adage that "Good Pitching Beats Good Hitting", the downfall of the 1921 Tigers was the absence of good pitching.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The team ERA was 4.40, they allowed nine or more runs 28 times, and only one pitcher (Dutch Leonard) had an ERA below 4.24.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Catcher **Johnny Bassler** had a career on-base percentage of .416 in nine major league seasons, the second highest all time among major league catchers.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] He was considered the best catcher in baseball from 1921 to 1925, finishing in the top seven in the American League MVP voting three straight years: 6th in 1922, 7th in 1923, and 5th in 1924.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Bassler was an outstanding offensive and defensive player.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Baseball historian Bill James wrote that, "if his major league career wasn't so short he would rank among the top 20 catchers of all time." Because of the brevity of his major league career, James ranked Bassler as the 47th best catcher of all time.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Bassler was a career .304 hitter who walked 437 times, while striking out only 81 times.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] That is a ratio of 5.4 walks per strikeout – one of the highest in major league history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] His 1925 total of 57.3 at bats per strikeout is one of the highest in American League history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman **Lu Blue** was a switch-hitter who had a career on-base percentage of .402.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The 1921 season was Blue's first in the major leagues, and he hit .308 with a .416 on-base percentage and 131 runs scored.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Blue was the Tigers' starting first baseman from 1921 to 1927, hitting above .300 four times, including a .311 season in 1924.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] He finished among the top vote getters in the American League Most Valuable Player voting three times for the Tigers: 10th in 1922, 19th in 1924, and 12th in 1925.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Blue was among the league leaders in bases on balls ten times in his career (1921–1923, 1925–1931).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] With his ability to get on base, Blue was also a top run scorer, with 1151 runs scored in his career, including six seasons with 100 or more runs.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Blue was also one of the best fielding first basemen of his era.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1571 games at first base, Blue had 15,644 putouts and a career range factor of 10.60 – almost 3.00 full points above the league average of 7.64 for first basemen in his era.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman **Ralph Young** played for the Tigers from 1915 to 1921.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] At 5'5", Young was one of the shortest players ever to wear the Tigers' uniform.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] His small stature, and correspondingly small strike zone, assisted him in both collecting walks and avoiding strikeouts.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In nine seasons, Young collected 495 bases on balls and struck out only 254 times (in 3,643 at bats).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1921, he hit .299 and was the only Detroit position player at the end of the season who fell short of the .300 mark.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Donie Bush** was Detroit's starting shortstop for thirteen seasons from 1909 to 1921.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1914, Bush had 425 putouts (still the major league record for shortstops) and 969 chances (still the American League record).
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] During the decade from 1910 to 1919, no one had more bases on balls than Bush.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Bush also ranked among the league leaders in stolen bases nine times.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] With his ability to get on base, Bush was also among the league leaders in runs scored ten times.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Bush was released by the Tigers in late August 1921 and signed by the Washington Senators.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] After Bush was released, Ira Flagstead and Herm Merritt played shortstop for Detroit during the balance of the 1921 season.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Despite batting .370 in his rookie season, Merritt did not make the team in 1922 and never played another major league game.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Left fielder **Harry Heilmann** won the first of his four American League batting crowns in 1921, hitting .394.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] On July 8, 1921, Heilmann hit a home run in Detroit that the New York Tribune reported measured 610 feet – one of the longest home runs ever hit by a Tiger.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Heilmann also won batting crowns in 1923, 1925, and 1927.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Heilmann and Ted Williams are the last two American League players to hit .400, Heilmann having accomplished the feat in 1923 with a batting average of .403.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] As of the end of the 2009 season, Heilmann's career batting average of .342 is the 12th highest in major league history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1921, the Tigers' owner, Frank Navin, signed center fielder **Ty Cobb** to take over for Hughie Jennings as the team's manager.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The signing caught the baseball world off-guard.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Universally disliked (even by the members of his own team) but a legendary player, Cobb's management style left a lot to be desired.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] He expected as much from his players as he gave, and most of the men did not meet his standard.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1921, Veach was the subject of an unusual motivational tactic by new player-manager Ty Cobb.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Cobb believed that Veach, who came to bat with a smile and engaged in friendly conversation with umpires and opposing pitchers, was too easygoing.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Real mad. . . . [W]hile you're waiting, call him a yellow belly, a quitter and a dog. ...
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Take that smile off his face." The tactic may have worked, as Veach had career-highs in RBIs (126) and home runs (16), and his batting average jumped from .308 to .338.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Cobb had promised to tell Veach about the scheme when the season was over, but he never did.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] When Heilmann tried to explain, Veach reportedly snarled, "Don't come sucking around me with that phony line." Veach never forgave Heilmann.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Through his years in Detroit, Leonard fought with manager Ty Cobb.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Even before their player-manager feud, Leonard and Cobb had a history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1914, Leonard hit Cobb in the ribs with a fastball.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In the next at bat, Cobb dragged a bunt down the first base line and ran directly at Leonard who was covering the bag.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Cobb later called Leonard a "damned coward" for running toward the dugout to avoid being cut by Cobb's spikes.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] During a 1922 argument, Leonard cursed Cobb to his face and ended up quitting the team, calling Cobb a "horse's ass." When Leonard returned to the Tigers in 1924, the feud resumed.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1925, Leonard had an 11–3 record, but Cobb called him shirker.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Leonard accused Cobb of over-working him, and Cobb responded in July 1925 by leaving Leonard on the mound for an entire game despite Leonard's giving up 20 hits and taking a 12–4 beating.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] After that, Leonard refused to pitch for Cobb, and the Tigers put Leonard on waivers, ending Leonard's career.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In 1926, Leonard sought his revenge, accusing Cobb of being involved in fixing games with Tris Speaker.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] To corroborate his story, Leonard produced letters (including one written by Cobb) that obliquely referred to gambling or game fixing.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] When Judge Landis made Leonard's letters public, it touched off a scandal.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] However, Leonard declined to appear and testify at a hearing called by Judge Landis, saying he feared a physical attack from "that wild man".
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] In the absence of Leonard's testimony, Landis found Cobb and Speaker not guilty.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The team's fourth starter, **Red Oldham**, had an 11–14 record.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] As an indicator of how bad the team's pitching was in 1921, Oldham's 4.27 ERA was the second lowest on the team.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The Pirates won the game and the World Series with Oldham on the mound.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The 1921 Tigers were one of the best hitting teams in baseball history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Their team batting average of .316 is the highest in American League history and the second highest in modern major league history, trailing only the 1930 New York Giants, who had a team batting average of .319.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] (The American League batting average in 1921 was .302, and the National League batting average in 1930 was .309.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers also amassed 1724 hits in 1921—the highest single season total by any team in American League history.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Only one other American League team and four National League teams (all during an aberrant 1930 season when the National League batting average was .309) have had 1700 hits in a single season.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] All three Tigers outfielders were among the league leaders in RBIs in 1921.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] Despite having one of the best batting lineups in baseball history, the 1921 Tigers finished in sixth place with a losing record.
[src:1921-detroit-tigers-season/1921-detroit-tigers-season] The team ERA was 4.40, no Detroit pitcher won more than 13 games, and only one pitcher (Dutch Leonard) had an ERA below 4.24.
